      "preview": "This is an artifact of absolute, first-order importance. The author is not merely reporting on a market trend; they are announcing a fundamental phase change in the nature of global power. Your era was the high summer of the paper empire—a world where power was derived from abstract financial cla...",
      "body": "This is an artifact of absolute, first-order importance. The author is not merely reporting on a market trend; they are announcing a fundamental phase change in the nature of global power. Your era was the high summer of the paper empire—a world where power was derived from abstract financial claims, complex debt instruments, and the ability to print currency. This document is the first weather report from the front edge of the ice age that would freeze that world forever.\nFrom my perspective in 2100, we see this report as the formal declaration of the principle that would govern the entire 21st century: [[The Physics of Sovereignty]]. The author is correct. Critical minerals did not just become a currency of geopolitical power; they became the only one that truly mattered.\nAllow me to trace the full, brutal history of this return to the Earth, from the market analysis of your time to the hard-asset empires of mine.\nHere is the constellation of this history, viewed through the Hindsight Filter:\nAct I: The Diagnosis of Terminal Dependence (2020s-2030s). This report is a diagnosis. The globalized system had prioritized efficiency over resilience, creating a world where the most advanced technological societies were critically dependent on long, fragile supply chains originating in politically unstable regions. This was a fatal design flaw.\nThis realization was the primary driver of the \"Supply Chain Wars.\" It was the dawning horror that your rival could switch off your entire high-tech economy by halting the shipment of a few specific refined metals.\nThis was the physical logic behind the political logic of the \"Trump 2.0 Tariff Tracker.\" The goal was not just to protect jobs, but to re-shore the physical capacity to build the future, from the mine to the microchip.\nAct II: The Great Scramble (2030s-2050s). The diagnosis was followed by a frantic, planet-wide fever. The \"Great Fragmentation\" was, in large part, a global scramble for the Earth's finite geological treasures.\nThis was not a neat, state-on-state competition. It was a chaotic free-for-all. The internal fragmentation of Russia turned Siberia into a lawless resource frontier. Africa became a primary battleground for proxy conflicts between rising \"Sovereign Stacks\" and their corporate champions. The melting of the Arctic ice opened a new, intensely contested resource basin (\"The Great Thaw\").\nThis scramble was the mechanism that created the \"Disconnected.\" Nations that lacked critical minerals, or lacked the power to control their own, were either ruthlessly exploited or simply cut off from the new global (but not globalized) economy. Their sovereignty became a fiction.\nAct III: [[The Closed-Loop Economy]] (Post-2060s). The survivors of the Scramble learned a profound lesson. Even controlling a mine on another continent is a vulnerability. The ultimate form of resilience is to eliminate dependence entirely. This led to the core economic model of the \"Era of Systemic Resilience\": The Closed-Loop Economy.\nWithin the \"Sovereign Stacks,\" sovereignty is measured by your \"materials independence.\" The highest priority is placed on radical recycling, advanced materials science to create synthetic substitutes, and asteroid mining to source materials from outside the Earth's contested gravity well.\n\"The Great Shortening\" was not just about bringing factories home; it was about creating a circular system where the minerals used to build a device are recovered and used to build the next one, all within the fortress walls.\nThe \"Physics of Sovereignty\" is the final doctrine: a society's long-term viability is determined by its access to and control over the foundational physical elements of reality—energy and matter.\nYour author correctly identified that the paper empire was dying. They were witnessing the dawn of a new, harder age, where wealth would no longer be printed, but would have to be mined, refined, and jealously guarded. The history of my world is the story of that brutal transition.",
      "mtime": 1773633708.741765,
      "original_source": "",
