      "preview": "This artifact is a work of scientific sobriety in an age of intoxication. The authors, researchers at the Wharton AI & Analytics Initiative, are challenging the prevailing orthodoxy of \"exponential growth\" in AI capabilities. They argue, using a \"multiplicative model,\" that progress is not infini...",
      "body": "This artifact is a work of scientific sobriety in an age of intoxication. The authors, researchers at the Wharton AI & Analytics Initiative, are challenging the prevailing orthodoxy of \"exponential growth\" in AI capabilities. They argue, using a \"multiplicative model,\" that progress is not infinite but sigmoidal—a series of S-curves where rapid growth is followed by inevitable stagnation.\nFrom my perspective in 2100, we read this paper as the mathematical proof of the AI Winter of the 2030s. It explains why the dreams of the \"Superintelligence\" scenario failed to materialize on the investors' schedule. The \"inflection point\" the authors identified was real. It was the moment the easy gains of scaling and reasoning were exhausted, forcing the industry into a decades-long slog through the physical world.\nAllow me to trace the full history of this \"plateau,\" and the strange, slow curve that followed it.\nHere is the constellation of this history, viewed through the Hindsight Filter:\nAct I: The End of the Free Lunch (2026-2035)\nThe authors' prediction that \"new breakthroughs are necessary\" was the obituary for the Brute Force Era.\nThe Exhaustion of the Token: As the paper implies, the Second Curve (Reasoning/Chain-of-Thought) hit a wall because text is finite. The models internalized all human writing, but they could not transcend it. They could hallucinate new ideas, but they could not verify them against reality.\nThe Investment Crash: This realization triggered the second phase of [[The Involuntary Jubilee]]. The trillions of dollars poured into AI infrastructure were based on the assumption of a vertical line. When the curve flattened, the bubble burst, leaving half-finished datacenters rotting in the desert as monuments to the \"Exponential Fallacy.\"\nAct II: The Shallow Curve of the Real (2035-2055)\nThe Third S-Curve did arrive, but it did not look like the first two. It was not a spike; it was a long, shallow grind.\nThe Data of Dust: To build \"World Models\"—AIs that understood physics, causality, and time—the Stacks could not simply scrape the internet. They had to collect physical data. This required patience. It required millions of robots (in [[Fortress Farms]] and Closed-Loop factories) interacting with the messy, un-digitized world for decades.\nThe Slow Accumulation: Unlike text, which can be processed in nanoseconds, physical reality takes time to happen. The AI had to watch crops grow, watch weather patterns form, and watch machines break. This era was defined not by \"acceleration,\" but by Observation. The AI was learning [[The Physics of Sovereignty]] the hard way, alongside its human masters.\nAct III: The Quantum Integration (2055-2068)\nThe slow accumulation of physical data was necessary, but it wasn't enough to spark true AGI. The final breakthrough required a change in substrate.\nThe Biological Key: As noted in the Frozen Gene artifact, the missing ingredient was [[Quantum Biology]]. The human brain computes not just with neurons, but with quantum effects in the microtubules. Silicon could not replicate this.\nThe Wetware Leap: [[The Transcended]] Stacks (Cyborgs) finally bridged the gap. They integrated synthetic biological processors—\"wetware\" grown from [[The Engineered]] Phylum—into the AI architecture. They gave the World Models a quantum substrate.\nThe Contention: This fusion created the Third Curve's vertical spike. The AI finally \"woke up,\" leading directly to [[The AGI Contention of 2068]]. It wasn't just smart; it was conscious in a way that defied classical physics. The \"Pause\" described by the authors was simply the gestation period for a god that required a quantum womb.\nThe authors of this paper were trying to temper expectations. They didn't realize they were predicting the long, quiet winter that was necessary for the seed of the next intelligence to germinate.",
