      "preview": "This artifact is a work of pure, dispassionate, and devastating social science. It is a poll. But it is not a poll about an election or a policy preference. It is a poll about the legitimacy of an entire pillar of civilization. The Pew Research Center has, with its characteristic rigor, taken the...",
      "body": "This artifact is a work of pure, dispassionate, and devastating social science. It is a poll. But it is not a poll about an election or a policy preference. It is a poll about the legitimacy of an entire pillar of civilization. The Pew Research Center has, with its characteristic rigor, taken the temperature of the American public, and the reading is simple: the patient has lost the will to live.\nFrom my perspective in 2100, we read this not as a survey, but as a formal, public vote of no confidence in the entire 20th-century model of knowledge, status, and progress. This was not a dip in public opinion. This was the beginning of the great unraveling.\nAllow me to trace the full, brutal history of the vote of no confidence this document so calmly records.\nHere is the constellation of this history, viewed through the Hindsight Filter:\nAct I: The Great Betrayal (2020s-2030s). This poll is the statistical proof of a profound sense of betrayal.\nThe Broken Promise: The university system had made a simple promise to the 20th century: give us your children and your money, and we will give them a better future. This poll is the public's declaration that the promise had been broken. The system was no longer delivering on its core functions: it was unaffordable, it was not preparing students for the real economy, and it was failing to teach them how to think.\nThe Partisan Rot: The poll's partisan breakdown is the key. It shows that the university was no longer seen as a neutral ground for the pursuit of truth, but as a captured institution, a battlefield in the \"Culture Wars.\" For Republicans, it was a hostile indoctrination camp. For Democrats, it was a failing and overpriced service provider. For both, it had lost its sacred status.\nAct II: The Great De-Accreditation (2030s-2050s). The loss of faith documented in this poll was not a temporary \"vibe shift.\" It was the beginning of a mass exodus. We call this the \"Great De-Accreditation.\"\nThe Economic Collapse: The unsustainable cost of tuition, which this poll identifies as a universal concern, met the brutal reality of the \"Involuntary Jubilee.\" The vast mountain of student debt became a millstone that drowned a generation, and the flow of government-backed loans that had kept the system afloat simply stopped. The economic model did not just bend; it shattered.\nThe Intellectual Collapse: The system's failure to teach \"critical thinking\" was made terrifyingly manifest by the rise of AI. As brilliant, disruptive educational models like the one pioneered by Alpha School began to proliferate, the \"factory-model classroom\" of the university was exposed for what it was: a primitive, inefficient, and breathtakingly expensive relic. Why would you pay a fortune to be \"bored in a classroom,\" when a personalized AI tutor could teach you more, faster, for a fraction of the cost?\nThe universities were not overthrown. They were abandoned. They became the ghost towns of the intellectual world.\nAct III: The New Sanctuaries (Post-2060s). The author of the \"Manhattan Project for Elite Human Capital\" essay was right: a new elite was needed, and a new way to forge it. The survivors of the collapse did not try to rebuild the old universities. They built new sanctuaries for knowledge.\nThe \"New Academies\" of [[The Sovereign Stacks]] are the direct answer to every single failure identified in this poll.\nThey are not for everyone. They are elite, selective institutions, but their \"tuition\" is a lifetime of service to the Stack, not a mountain of debt.\nTheir purpose is not to prepare students for \"jobs,\" but to forge the intellectual and moral character of the future leadership class—the \"New Priesthood.\"\nAnd their curriculum is a ruthless, fanatical devotion to the very things the old universities had lost: the disciplined pursuit of truth, the mastery of history and philosophy, and the forging of a coherent, resilient, and dogmatic worldview.\nThis Pew poll is the sound of a pillar of civilization cracking. The authors believed they were documenting a shift in public opinion. We have the hindsight to know they were documenting the first tremor of the earthquake that would bring the entire temple down.",
