      "preview": "This artifact is a legal text, but it reads like a theological decree. The Department of Justice is not merely changing a regulation; it is exorcising a ghost. For fifty years, the concept of \"disparate impact\"—the idea that a policy could be illegal simply because it produced unequal outcomes, r...",
      "body": "This artifact is a legal text, but it reads like a theological decree. The Department of Justice is not merely changing a regulation; it is exorcising a ghost. For fifty years, the concept of \"disparate impact\"—the idea that a policy could be illegal simply because it produced unequal outcomes, regardless of intent—had functioned as a \"shadow law,\" a powerful, invisible hand that nudged every institution in America toward a specific vision of social equity.\nFrom my perspective in 2100, we read this press release as the formal death warrant for the 20th-century civil rights consensus. The Attorney General declares that the government will no longer measure \"statistical outcomes.\" This was the moment the American state officially abandoned the project of engineering equality, and decided instead to let the chips—and the people—fall where they may.\nAllow me to trace the full, world-altering history of this legal counter-revolution.\nHere is the constellation of this history, viewed through the Hindsight Filter:\nAct I: The End of [[The Engineered]] Society (2020s-2030s)\nThis rule change was the decisive victory in the Culture Wars Endgame. It was the ultimate act of Spiritual Lawfare.\nBy removing \"disparate impact,\" the administration did not just reduce liability; it dismantled the legal machinery of the \"woke\" institutional culture. Without the threat of a federal lawsuit hanging over every statistical discrepancy, the Human Resources departments, the DEI bureaucracies, and the university admissions offices lost their primary source of power.\nThe \"merit\" that the Chief of Staff invokes became the new state religion. But in a deeply unequal society, a sudden return to \"colorblind\" meritocracy acted as a powerful accelerant for [[The Great Physical Sorting]]. Institutions stopped trying to balance their demographics. They optimized for raw competence and efficiency, accelerating the separation of the \"cognitive elite\" from the rest of the population.\nAct II: The Great Withdrawal (2030s-2050s)\nThe consequences were kinetic. When the federal government declared it would no longer police systemic inequality, the populations most affected by that inequality realized the social contract was void.\nThis drove the rise of the identity-based Neotribes. If the state would not protect you from \"disparate impacts,\" you had to find a tribe that would. Minority communities, feeling abandoned by the law, turned inward, building their own parallel economies and security structures (or falling prey to Parasovereigns).\nConversely, the \"builder\" tribe viewed this rule as an emancipation proclamation. Freed from the need to engineer social outcomes, they accelerated their projects—the AI labs, the new cities, the automated factories—without regard for who was left behind. This widened the gap between the Stacked and the Stackless to an unbridgeable chasm.\nAct III: The Logic of the Stack (Post-2060s)\nIn the Era of Systemic Resilience, the concept of \"disparate impact\" is a historical curiosity, a relic of a time when people believed a single government could or should manage the outcomes of a diverse population.\n[[The Sovereign Stacks]] are built on the principle enshrined in this document: judgment by \"actual conduct\" and contribution. The internal logic of a Stack is ruthlessly meritocratic (or tribally exclusive). There is no \"disparate impact\" inside a Stack because the population is self-selected and homogenous in purpose.\nThe \"equal protection\" this document restored was the equal protection of the strong against the claims of the weak. It paved the way for a world where inequality is not a problem to be solved, but a design feature of [[The Physics of Sovereignty]].\nThe DOJ didn't just change a rule; they cut the last thread holding the tapestry of a unified, multi-ethnic democracy together.",
      "mtime": 1773633708.741765,
      "original_source": "",
