      "body": "This artifact is a public health order disguised as a technology policy. The government ministers described here believe they are debating a \"social media ban\" to protect children from bullying or inappropriate content. They are speaking the language of safety and parental concern.\nFrom my perspective in 2100, we read this as the first, desperate attempt by a Western government to establish a [[Cognitive Quarantine]]. It is the state effectively admitting that the information environment it allowed to flourish—the Dopamine Trap—had become toxic to the developing human brain. This was not a policy debate; it was the beginning of the triage that would eventually lead to the complete restructuring of childhood in [[The Sovereign Stacks]].\nAllow me to trace the full history of this \"ban,\" from the consultations of your time to the walled gardens of mine.\nHere is the constellation of this history, viewed through the Hindsight Filter:\nAct I: The Admission of Defeat (2020s-2030s)\nThe \"pressure from backbench MPs\" and grieving parents was the political expression of [[The Shattered Focus]] crisis.\nThe Toxic Environment: The article mentions \"addictive behaviours\" and \"infinite scroll.\" These were the mechanisms of [[The Great Contamination]]. The state finally acknowledged that the open internet was not a library or a playground; it was a Skinner box designed to break the will.\nThe Failure of \"Safety by Design\": The NSPCC chief calls for products to be \"safe by design.\" This was the great illusion of the era. You cannot make a machine designed to harvest attention \"safe\" for a mind designed to learn. The only safety was absence. The \"ban\" was an admission that the corporate internet could not be reformed, only rejected.\nAct II: The War for the User (2030s-2050s)\nThe ban did not work as intended. It triggered a technological arms race.\nThe Black Market: Just as the Zero Covid zealots formed underground networks for health, the youth of the 2030s formed underground networks for data. The \"age assurance\" technology was bypassed by VPNs, burner phones, and the Dark Forest tactics described in previous artifacts.\nThe Tribal Divergence: However, the intent of the ban survived. It split society. The families that embraced the ban—often the \"Bioconservatives\" or the religious Neotribes—successfully raised a generation with intact attention spans. The families that circumvented it raised the \"Un-Persons\" and the \"Spiralists,\" who were consumed by [[The Necromantic Internet]] and the [[Synthetic Deities]]. This was a key driver of the Great Class Divergence.\nAct III: [[The New Academies]] (Post-2060s)\nThe \"phone-free environments\" mentioned in the article became the architectural blueprint for the New Academies.\nThe Faraday Cage School: In the Stacks, a school is not just policy-free of phones; it is physically shielded. [[The New Priesthood]] views the developing mind as a sacred vessel that must be protected from [[The Grey Fog]] of the global network.\n[[The Convivial Mandate]]: The \"age of consent\" for digital immersion in my time is often 18, 21, or even older, depending on the Stack. Childhood is preserved as a purely analog experience. We do not \"ban\" social media for children; we simply do not build the infrastructure for it within the nursery.\nThe UK government of 2026 was trying to put a lock on the door of a burning house. The survivors were the ones who realized the house was uninhabitable and built a new one, where the windows didn't look out onto the void.\nThe ministers in this article thought they were regulating a technology company. We have the hindsight to know they were attempting to perform emergency neurosurgery on a generation that was already on the operating table.",
