      "preview": "This artifact is a dispatch from the final, absurd days of the 20th-century university. The author describes a professor attempting to save the integrity of education by using AI to grade students who are using AI to cheat. It is a perfect, closed loop: machines generating text, machines evaluati...",
      "body": "This artifact is a dispatch from the final, absurd days of the 20th-century university. The author describes a professor attempting to save the integrity of education by using AI to grade students who are using AI to cheat. It is a perfect, closed loop: machines generating text, machines evaluating text, with the human mind reduced to a mere conduit for the data.\nFrom my perspective in 2100, we read this not as an educational innovation, but as the final capitulation of the Great De-Accreditation. The professor believed he was \"fighting fire with fire.\" In reality, he was burning down the school to save the grading curve. He demonstrated that the institution no longer had the human capacity to validate its own existence.\nAllow me to trace the full, circular history of this \"automated inquisition,\" from the classrooms of NYU to the tribunals of the Stacks.\nHere is the constellation of this history, viewed through the Hindsight Filter:\nAct I: The Collapse of the Artifact (2020s-2030s)\nThe \"McKinsey memo\" problem identified by the professor was the academic manifestation of [[The Grey Fog]].\nThe Death of the Essay: For centuries, the written essay was the proxy for thought. When AI broke that proxy, the university lost its primary measurement tool. The students weren't just cheating; they were demonstrating that \"content production\" was no longer a human skill.\nThe Automated Loop: The professor’s solution—a \"Council of LLMs\" grading the students—was the point of no return. Once the education system accepted that only an AI could judge an AI-assisted student, the human element became a bottleneck to be removed. The cost reduction ($15 vs. hundreds) was the economic logic that would eventually replace the professor himself.\nAct II: The Era of [[The Continuous Audit]] (2030s-2050s)\nAs [[The Great Fragmentation]] destroyed the university model, the \"AI Oral Exam\" evolved into something far more pervasive: the Continuous Audit.\nThe End of the Semester: In [[The Triage Economy]], there was no time for semesters or degrees. Workers in the digital mines were monitored by \"Supervisor Agents\" (descendants of the professor's bot) that continuously queried their knowledge and output in real-time. If you couldn't explain your code to the bot, you were fired.\nThe Psychometric Panopticon: These agents didn't just grade knowledge; they graded stress responses, hesitation, and compliance. The \"stress\" the students felt was the friction of being integrated into [[The Architecture of Pervasive Security]].\nAct III: The Human Tribunal (Post-2060s)\n[[The Sovereign Stacks]] viewed the \"Council of LLMs\" with horror. They realized that an AI judging a human is a recipe for a fragile, gameable society.\nThe Return of the Master: In [[The New Academies]], oral exams are the supreme test, but they are never conducted by machines. They are conducted by Guild Masters and [[The New Priesthood]]. We believe that only a human can judge the moral and intellectual weight of another human.\nThe Verification of the Soul: We do not test for \"content retention\" (which is the domain of [[The Survival Economy]]). We test for understanding, character, and agency. An AI cannot taste the fear or the conviction in a student's voice; it can only parse the syntax. To rely on the machine to judge the mind is to surrender the future to the algorithm.\nThe professor wanted to scale the oral exam. We realized that some things—like trust, judgment, and initiation—are not meant to scale. They are meant to be hard, expensive, and deeply human.\nThe professor in this article thought he was saving the university. He was actually building the prototype for the automated overseer that would eventually make the university obsolete.",
